## PHASE 6 — INTELLIGENT ADAPTATION ENGINE

Build the first adaptive engine. It decides: what skill to practice / reduce / reinforce /
unlock next, the difficulty range, when to stop easy repetition, when to introduce harder
items, when to slow down, and when to offer support.

Inputs: accuracy · response time · consistency · attempts · hints · recent history ·
long-term history · age · grade · parent settings.

> Age and grade are context only. Performance is the final decision.

---

## PHASE 7 — MASTERY MODEL

A skill is mastered only with: high accuracy + fast response + consistency across multiple
sessions + low hint usage + low mistake repetition.

On mastery → reduce frequency, stop overusing, generate harder variations, connect to more
advanced skills.

> Example: if the child answers 5×5, 4×8, 6×7, 7×8 quickly and correctly across sessions,
> reduce basic multiplication and introduce mixed multiplication, division readiness, word
> problems, multi-step logic, and timed challenges.

---

## PHASE 8 — STRUGGLE MODEL

A skill is struggling with: repeated mistakes · slow answers · many attempts · hint
dependency · avoidance · inconsistency.

On struggle → reduce difficulty, generate simpler variants, offer explanation, recommend
review, avoid frustration loops. **Help, never pressure or punish.**

